   NAME
	EVAL - Evaluates simple expressions.

   FORMAT
	EVAL <value1> [<operation>] [<value2...Value3>] [TO <file>]
	     [LFORMAT=<string>]

   TEMPLATE
	VALUE1/A,OP,VALUE2/M,TO/K,LFORMAT/K,HEX/S

   PATH
	C:EVAL

   FUNCTION
	EVAL is used to evaluate and print the answer of an integer
	expression. The fractional portion of input values and final 
	results, if any, is truncated (cut off).

	<Value1> and <value2> may be in decimal, hexadecimal, or octal
	numbers. Decimal numbers are the default. Hexadecimal numbers are
	indicated by a leading 0x or #X or $. Octal numbers are 
	indicated by either a leading 0 or a leading #. Alphabetical 
	characters are indicated by a leading single quote (').

	The output format defaults to decimal, unless the HEX switch is
	used; however, you can use the LFORMAT keyword to select another
	format. See below.

	The supported operations and their corresponding symbols are shown 
	in the table below:

	    Operation            Symbol
	    addition             +
	    subtraction          -
	    multiplication       *
	    division             /
	    modulo               mod (or %)
	    AND                  &
	    OR                   or (or |)
	    NOT                  ~
	    left shift           lsh
	    right shift          rsh
	    negation             -
	    exclusive OR         xor (or ^)
	    bitwise equivalence  eqv

	EVAL can be used in scripts to act as a counter for loops. In that
	case, the TO option, which sends the output of EVAL to a file, is 
	very useful.
   
   LFORMAT
	The LFORMAT keyword specifies the formatting string used to print 
	the answer. You may use the following arguments:

	%X - prints an heXadecimal number
	%O - prints an Octal number
	%N - prints a decimal number
	%C - prints a Character

	The %X and %O options require a number of digits specification 
	(e.g., %X8 gives 8 digits of hex output). When using the LFORMAT 
	keyword, you can specify that a new line should be printed by 
	including a *N in your string.

	Note: Be aware that as of AmigaOS 3.2, EVAL now correctly 
	distinguishes mathematical priorities between operators, so 
	results are now different, but correct (EVAL 2+4*3 results in 24, 
	in previous incarnations it would have thrown 18 as a result).

   EXAMPLES
      1> EVAL 3 + 4 * 5
      23
   
	    1> EVAL 4 * -5
	    -20

	    1> EVAL 0x4f / 010 LFORMAT="The answer is %X4*N"
	    The answer is 0009

	This divides hexadecimal 4f (79) by octal 10 (8), yielding 0009, 
	the integer portion of the decimal answer 9.875. (The 1> prompt 
	would have appeared immediately after the 0009 if *N had not been 
	specified in the LFORMAT string.)

	Assume you were using the following script, called Loop:

	   ; demonstrate a loop using eval and skip
	   .Key loop/a
	   .Bra {
	   .Ket }
	   ECHO >ENV:Loop {loop}
	   LAB start
	   ECHO "Loop #" noline
	   TYPE ENV:Loop
	   EVAL <ENV:Loop >NIL: to=T:Qwe{$$} value2=1 op=- ?
	   TYPE >ENV:Loop T:Qwe{$$}
	   IF val $loop GT 0
	   SKIP start back
	   ENDIF
	   ECHO "done"

	If you were to type:

	    1> EXECUTE Loop 5
	    Loop #5
	    Loop #4
	    Loop #3
	    Loop #2
	    Loop #1
	    done

	The first ECHO command sends the number given as the loop 
	argument, entered as an argument of the EXECUTE command, to the 
	ENV:Loop file.

	The second ECHO command coupled with the TYPE command, displays 
	Loop # followed by the number given as the loop argument. In this 
	case, it displays Loop #5.

	The EVAL command takes the number in the ENV:Loop file as 
	<value1>. <Value2> is 1, and the operation is subtraction. The 
	output of the EVAL command is sent to the T:Qwe($$) file. In this 
	case, the value would be 4.

	The next TYPE command sends the value in the T:Qwe($$) file to the
	ENV:Loop file. In this case, it changes the value in ENV:Loop from 
	5 to 4.

	The IF statement states that as long as the value for Loop is 
	greater than 0, the script should start over. This results in the 
	next line being Loop #4.

	The script will continue until Loop is equal to 0.
